caption: A LES fusion spot for Asian twist on American food. We ordered cold brew coffee w/ milk along with Chinatown egg & cheese sando(sandwich) w/ bacon, which had perfect eggs. The hash browns were perfectly done and crispy. We also ordered Kale & Parmesan Biscuits & Gravy with dill and parsley garnish. Don’t take my word for it or how good the photo looks, give them a try. You will not be disappointed. The biscuits were crispy and the gravy was delicious! Highly recommend and will definitely go back here again! The staff was covid friendly and had sanitizers and outdoor seating available.

Probably one of my favorite Asian places in the area, Golden Diner located underneath the Manhattan Bridge, thematically operating in Chinatown. The cool thing about it is that they serve a mixture of Asian and Classic US cuisine. Yoo's mushroom Reuben quesadilla ($14) is awesome. The greasy tortilla taste did not stand out at first, but when dipped in pink Russian seasoning, the oozing dishes were like the best drinking sides in the world. The wonton ($13) has a layer of pork dumplings, topped with a stack of shredded cheese and elegant mushroom slices, sprinkled with cardamom powder. It feels as refreshing as minestrone soup or Yankee bean soup. We are lucky to have Yoo bring us next time we have the flu. Diners are also not known for their excellent pasta, but the hearty, curly Taiwanese noodles ($18) are so eye-catching they may become the belt in the next Gucci collection-will make you reconsider. Although the taste of vognole is not as salty as its stewed clam dish, the fermented black bean sauce is precisely a home-cooked dish we don’t know. Golden Diner was always famous for its picturesque location with a great spot near the Manhattan Bridge. The area is vibrant, yet pleasant.
Everything here is delish! What a gem in the neighborhood. Don't forget to order a slice of the Green Team Coffee Cake.

From all appearances, this place is your standard classic diner. But the food is so much better than that.  The black bean vongole isn’t on the normal menu, but hidden on a flap labeled “chef’s specials.” Order this. The combination of Taiwanese noodles, black bean sauce, and clams with breadcrumbs is savory and addictive. The noodles have great bite to them as well.  The kale and Parmesan biscuits and gravy are another thing you should definitely order. The chicken gravy is really good (leaning on salty), but the real star is the biscuits. They almost have the texture of a pound cake — really dense but somehow also very fluffy. Those biscuits alone are worth ordering the dish for.  The vegetalian hero is massive, but you can comfort yourself by saying it’s all veggies anyway.  Service is efficient and friendly. Decor is on theme without being too campy. Beware of loud trains passing overhead, which might interrupt conversation.

The burger, chicken wings, and fried squid were my favorites.  Service: 10/10 Fast, friendly, glasses were always full.  Ambiance: 6/10 It's a really small place with a diner feel. Great place for a bite! It has a classic diner feel with some asian cuisine influences. The place is a bit small so definitely come early or come during off times. I think they do Yelp waitlist so definitely do that to save yourself some time.  My partner and I came on a Saturday night at 6ish and there was no wait. However, more people started showing up as we were halfway through our meal so it does get filled up later in the night.  For food I got the seasonal bibimbap and my partner got the chicken Katsu sando. The bibimbap used fresh seasonal veggies and used some type of grain I don’t remember. The portion was a bit small but the flavors were strong. I think it was vegan friendly too so if you’re looking for that then this is a good option. I think they are well known for their chicken Katsu sando and I could see why. First off, it’s huge. It’s very filling even for one person. My favorite part was the chicken and the slaw. The chicken was juicy and had a nice crunch. The slaw with the bulldog sauce was so good. Tangy and crunchy. For dessert we got their seasonal apple bingsoo. It was refreshing and if you like apples it’s like eating apple pie! Will have to come back to try more of their menu!

An all American diner with Asian influences in their menu? Sign me up. Found this place online and after seeing pictures of the chicken katsu club sandwich, I knew I had to go there. Luckily I had to fly to NYC for a wedding. So this place was my #1 spot I had to visit. The flight from Korea to NYC is roughly 13 hours, but after eating here, the travel time was worth it. Clean facilities and a friendly staff just add to the simple fact that the food here is amazing. The chicken katsu club was everything I expected and more. Luckily my wife and the groom to be accompanied me when I came here so I got to try bites of their food. My wife got the breakfast sandwich, and wow, that scrambled egg in the sandwich. Just so delicious. My friend loved it so much, that he went the next day for lunch with his family. It was great to show a New Yorker a great New York restaurant. Overall, if you want delicious diner food. Go here. If you want great delicious diner food with a twist. Go here. If you just want delicious food, you need to go the Golden Diner.

This place is a true gem! Was lucky enough to sit at the counter and watch Sam, the chef and owner, and his #2 prepare all the foods with dedication and care.  The quality is supreme which makes all the difference with simple breakfast foods. Sam checked the temperature and quality of every burrito and sandwich and would send it back or prepare it again if it did not reach his standards.  The egg sandwich was a soft bun with a crunchy hash brown toast and melt in your mouth eggs. The combination of textures was amazing and delicious.  The burrito was delicious, with pico de gallo creating a different taste sensation when combined with hash crunch, eggs and soft wrap. Yum, we had the sandwich, breakfast burrito, chardonnay, coffee, bacon, and tofu scramble. Breakfast was delicious 👌 😋
Fresh food and fantastic service. They treat you like family! What more would you want?!
Great spot! Asian fusion diner food. Menu changes often. Cozy place. Food is perfection. Coffee is fantastic.
If they have the sandwich special with a hash brown on it, GET IT. Best breakfast sandwich I’ve had in a while. Beautiful space and really nice people.
Outstanding across the board. This is a quaint, old school feel diner with some nice twists to the menu. The service was excellent and the food was reasonably priced. Highly recommended.
A small, simple menu, but everything was delicious. The service was also friendly and attentive
(Translated by Google) Cleaning, cleaning, and an exquisite education, worth knowing  (Original) Limpieza limpieza limpieza y una educación exquisita, digno de conocer

The staff was attentive and friendly. The small space was clean and tastefully laid out to make it feel nostalgic. The miss for me is in the menu when thinking "Diner". That name indicates a full menu. The menu here is minimal. For instance, for breakfast there are eggs and bacon, but you won't find Canadian Bacon, etc. The food was all well prepared and presented well. Being greedy, I'd like more Keto friendly items such as grilled chicken vs breaded, but had options via the breakfast sides.

Just had an excellent meal here! Came with a group and we shared all of the sandwiches - the burrito, the katsu sandwich, the avocado, the veggie one... WOW. Really surprisingly tasty and special. Came on a Sunday and the place had super chill, good vibes. We waited maybe 15 min for our table of 6. Great music/ambiance (old school r&b and some hip hop), nice crowd, friendly service. I met the chef/owner Sam who was right behind the counter cooking our meal. Great classic diner spot with a modern Asian twist. Pro tip: The matcha coffee cake is extra matcha-y and not overly sweet (exactly as I like it)! Price is right too. Totally affordable. I had a really positive experience and am coming back in a couple weeks haha. A true new gem!
Very friendly staff and the best diner food I’ve had in the city - especially for the price. Can’t wait for the grand opening.
Good food great service  very clean

(Translated by Google) The place is small and has a few dishes, but the chicken club sandwich is one of the best ever eaten!  (Original) Il posto è un piccolo e ha pochi piatti, però il club sandwich di pollo è uno dei migliori mai mangiati!
Breakfast was delicious! Excited to have this in the neighborhood.
Golden Diner is amazing! Their friendly staff, delicious food and welcoming vibe make this place a must visit! Don't forget to try the matcha coffee cake :)
10 15 minute wait on Saturday Morning Brunch
So delicious!  Love the fresh take on some familiar and classic sandwiches. Can’t wait until they are open evenings.
Great service and food for luncg! Excited for when they add dinner into the mix!
What a tremendous addition to this tremendous neighborhood.  Friendly and inviting, and everything is made with the care that makes it surprisingly better than you expected.  Welcome and bravo!

Food is dope, vibes are good, what more do you need to know? A bit of a hidden gem deep in Chinatown. In a sea of fried noodles and soup dumplings, it's an oasis of classic comfort diner food with a flourish of delightful surprises i.e. "is that fresh turmeric in my avo toast?!" Why yes. Yes it is.

an excellent addition to the neighborhood. this is straight up good food made with great ingredients. i'm looking forward to dinner and enjoying an expanded menu that's coming in the near future. yes, the matzo ball soups is great. i had the chicken katsu club sandwich with some very nice french fries.
Great new addition to the neighborhood, food was delicious and service was friendly. Will definitely come back to try more items.  Must order the chicken katsu sandwich!!
Great food. Had tofu scramble and bacon, it was delicious!! Menu has a nice mix of food with vegetarian and vegan options. Definitely want to go back and try more of their dishes!!
Great crispy bacon and home fries!

The best matzoh ball soup I’ve ever eaten in a restaurant. Yes, I’ve been to a number of New York’s famous Jewish delis. Small, marble-sized matzoh balls are, let’s face it, not that satisfying. Giant baseball- or even softball- sized matzoh balls are impressive, but often cold in the middle and there’s nothing worse than that. The matzoh balls at Golden Diner are egg-sized and heated all the way through 😋

the yuba hero was delightfully fresh and delicious, and the dining space has a very open, inviting, and comfortable vibe. I'll definitely be back to try the matzoh ball soup and chicken katsu sandwich! 🤤🤤
Elevated comfort food. Yuba (tofu skin) hero was a standout. Grab a matcha crumb cake to go.

Look you internet trolls- this restaurant isn’t even open yet and so it makes no sense to have negative reviews. It was featured on Grub Street in their fall preview of best new restaurants to watch. The chef is a Torrisi alum and NOMA intern so you know it’s gonna be dope. All you haters just stop. Think it opens early 2019.
